Patient is a healthcare worker who received COVID-19 vaccine through her employee health vaccination program. 2 days later, patient developed subconjunctival hemorrhages, then fever, headache, and blisters on trunk. Over the next several days the blisters developed into pruritic pustules including extremities, palms, and soles and patient had increasing joint pain and stiffness in extremities. Patient was seen by rheumatology who thought this may be flare of her psoriatic arthritis or a viral etiology. They deferred treatment with steroids since she was due to receive her 2nd dose of the COVID-19 vaccine soon. Patient received 2nd dose of COVID-19 vaccine and called employee health 2 days later with fever, headache, nausea, swollen lymph nodes, rash spreading to head, and congestion. COVID-19 swab neg. She was seen at an urgent care and diagnosed with pneumonia and was started on doxycycline. Three days later, she presented to the emergency department and was admitted with fever, cough, sob, continued rash (macular and pustular), reported worst headache of life and continued worst arthritis flare of life. Patient was seen multiple times by a variety of clinicians throughout her illness including dermatology, rheumatology, emergency medicine, and internal medicine. Patient had an extensive work-up to identify causes including negative blood cultures, RPR, varicella PCR, respiratory pathogen panel, gonorrhea/chlamydia PCR, HIV, and lumbar puncture with bacterial, viral, and fungal testing. The most common themes of provider assessments were that patient had a psoriatic arthritis flare (worst of life per patient report) which may have been related to the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. After 2nd dose of vaccine, patient was diagnosed with guttate psoriasis which was thought to be either related to COVID-19 vaccine or Humira as TNFi has been linked to guttate psoriasis, although Humira was not a new med, and this had not happened in the past.
OTHER_MEDS: Humira, celecoxib, leflunobide, lisdexamfetamine, omeprazole, tizanidine, amlodipine, COVID-19 vaccine

The pain went away after about 2 days.  Today, (eight days later) I woke up with a horrible itch at the injection site.  I started to scratch the area (still half asleep) and could feel it swelling with every scratch.  When I got up and looked in the mirror, it was hard as a rock, swollen, and about the size of a baseball.  The swelling in the center was white and looked almost like cottage cheese bumps under the skin.  I drew a circle around the swelling and went to see clients for the rest of the day.  Tonight, when I got home I drew another circle to see how much the swelling had increased.  It had increased quite significantly.  The area (that is rock hard) is about 8 inches from top to bottom and four inch width.  It is rock hard still, itchy, and hot to the touch.  The area is red, but the white cottage cheese bumps are down a bit.  I have also had a headache for two days prior to the swelling.  I thought this was unrelated, but I don't think that anymore.  I normally do not get headaches.  If the swelling has increased by tomorrow, I will seek medical attention.

After being observed for approximately 20 minutes and patient walked to her car without assistance I was called to assess the patient in the parking lot for troubles breathing.  EMS was called as I made my way outside.  Upon my arrival patient was leaning out of the car and stating that she could not breath.  She was able to tell me that she was allergic to penicillin.  Oxygen was immediately placed on the patient with minimal relief.  Lung sounds were coarse throughout.  She then  began to vomit about every 20-30 seconds.  Epipen was administered in the right leg with no relief.  Patient continued to complain of troubles breathing and vomiting.  A second epipen was administered in the patients right arm again with no relief.  A few minutes later patient was given racemic epinephrine through the oxygen mask.  There appeared to be mild improvement in her breathing as she appeared more comfortable, but still complaining of shortness of breath and vomiting.  When EMS arrived patient was unable to transport herself to the stretcher.  When EMS and clinical staff transferred patient to the stretcher she became unresponsive.  She appeared to still be breathing.  She did not respond to verbal stimuli.  Per ED report large amount of fluid was suctioned from the patients lungs following intubation in the ambulance.  When patient arrived to the ED she was extubated and re-intubated without difficulty and further fluid was suctioned.  At that time patient was found to be in PEA, shock was delivered.  Shortly thereafter no cardiac activity was found and patient pronounced dead.

He rushed over to me and called my name several times before I became conscious. He estimates it was a span of about 30 seconds. When I awoke, I immediately began to cold sweat and dry heave several times. Then I became cold and was shivering. My husband then transported me to the hospital emergency room. I received a cardiac test, which they said was good. I also received intravenous fluids and medication to treat pain and nausea. They drew labs which they said looked normal and  did an X-ray my right shoulder because I struck my head and shoulder on a night stand when I passed out. They released me about an hour later after having me stand and walk to ensure my blood pressure did not drop, causing me to feel faint again. They sent me home with a prescription for Zofran to help with any further nausea, advised me to take ibuprofen for head and shoulder pain and body aches and advised rest. They also said to return if any other incidents occur and to follow up with my family doctor if symptoms persist.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine EUA Event Description: Patient at hospital to receive her first dose of Pfizer Covid vaccine in left deltoid at ~1105.  ~15 minutes after administration c/o leftl arm feeling hot and appearing red.  Patient was observed for 45 minutes and given Benadryl 25 mg IM, Solumedrol 125 mg IM, and Pepcid 20 mg po.  The redness on her arm increased and her BP and pulse continued to be elevated.  She was transferred to ED for further evaluation a 1148.  patient walked to ED to be evaluated for allergic reaction. Pt. reports having an 1100 vaccine appointment. Pt. received vaccine, then c/o left arm redness/swelling.  HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: patient is a 36y female who presents to the ED with an allergic reaction. Pt reports she received the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine this morning at 1100, first dose, and noted a rash along the left arm where the injection site was. Pt notes she received the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine. Pt documents a rash along the left arm which she described as "itchy and tingling."  Patient initially had an area of redness following the injection site and then it extended down her entire arm to the wrist.  She states that she was wearing a tighter shirt and they had her change into a loose scribed top.  Patient denies any tongue swelling, throat swelling, itching, sneezing, syncope, presyncope, chest pain, shortness of breath double cough, nausea, or vomiting.  No prior history of allergic/anaphylactic reactions. Patient was monitored for 1 hr and had significant improvement of symptoms.  She was discharged in good condition and to return with any new, concerning, worsening symptoms. Advised to follow up with PCP in 2-3 days.  Dx: acute allergic reaction to COVID-19 Vaccine Provided Rx for Benadryl and Pepcid  Seen by PCP 1/22/2021 and internal reported filed, prompting VAERS report

Changing position seemed to help and went back to sleep. woke up about 5 am and checked the rash which was mostly gone except for the original spot where it began.  The rash and pressure seemed to be restricted to front left side below waist area. It is now 11:00 am 1/31/2021 and I am feeling fine, very little residual rash at initial site.   I had not read anything about delayed reactions as late as 3 1/2 days after the injection so wanted to report this event.

Instead, she told me to pull my sleeve down.  Approximately two hours after my vaccination, my shoulder started to stiffen and became painful. By evening, I lost most range of motion. Now, two days later, I cannot move my shoulder without searing pain. Lifting to the side is particularly difficult and painful. I cannot lift or push without pain.  A popping/cracking sound comes from my shoulder join. Ice and pain relievers do not ease the pain or increase range of motion. I plan on phoning my doctor this week to discuss additional treatment.

I spoke to the person in the disease office,and she told me she hadnt heard of anything like this and told me to call the Dr. I called my dr, who didnt quite know what to tell me,but this was a couple of days later,and by then i did find info on the internet,where some people said they took Benedryl. I took Benedryl then,and my Dr told me to take some Advil, though i dont know if it has helped or not. I am due for my second shot on Feb 11, and i assume i should ask for the shot in my right arm this time? In any case, i thought it important for me to report this as there are probably alot  more people who are receiving this effect,and if it is published more, there will be less concern when it occurs, at least i hope there should be no concer.n. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine on 1/29 at 5 pm and was feeling fine afterwards with only a slightly sore arm at the injection site.   Then yesterday, 1/30 around 6 pm, I started to have a very fast heart rate, despite not exerting myself and only sitting down at the time. Between 6-6:45 pm, I had a heart rate between 125-140 bpm, according to my fit bit device that tracks my heart rate on my wrist. Anyways, after that I was going to the bathroom and started to feel nauseous, light headed, felt hot and chills like a fever, abdominal pain and vision issues (blackening in some spots and blurry on and off) so I went to lay down. I didn't vomit and the chills/hot fever feeling went away in 15 minutes. I also took my temperature and it was normal. My abdominal pain continued but the light headedness and nausea and vision issues subsided. I was unable to get up and do other stuff, so I just slept it off. I'm feeling better this morning. I  had also drank about a half glass of wine (maybe 2 oz), so i'm not sure if that contributed to it, but i've never felt that way after drinking wine, especially that small of an amount. I had also drank this wine around 4 pm and that was 2.5 hours before I started feeling this way and did not drink anything on the day I received the injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 11:45 pm the same day I received my second Moderna injection for Covid, I woke up from sleep shivering uncontrollably. I felt like I was chilled to the bone and was shivering so hard my muscles all felt contracted. I did not have a fever at this time. I got extra blankets and tuned heat up and over next 45 minutes managed to decrease shivering. Around this time, I rechecked my temperature and had a fever of 101.7. I used tylenol and later motrin as the fever kept rising. I was in and out of sleep with severe body aches, arm pain at site of injection, and increasing fever even after taking ibuprofen an hour later. My temp eventually reached a max of 104.5 at which point I uncovered myself and got ice packs for my head and neck. I managed to get my fever down to about 102.6 and it stayed in that range until about 445am the next morning. I was finally able to get a little rest. When I woke at 815am, my fever was 100.5. From there, the more notable issues were the intense body and joint pains and skin sensitivity along with increasing arm pain at site of injection. My fever managed to stay low grade around 99.5 throughout the day but then started increasing again in the evening. At about 500pm, it was at 100.8. I took more medication to reduce it and was unable to sleep until about 2am still from the pain. I then slept for approx 6 hours into Sunday morning,  today, and have had no fever. I am improving with pains, but have noticed red blotchy areas near my injection site which still hurts immensely but is tolerable.
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia,  SVT, depression, anxiety, chronic back pain from multiple surgeries, high blood pressure

It is probably the worst I have felt in several years.  I had significant muscle pain and even laying on the couch was too uncomfortable.  I laid in bed and slept off and on.  Monday, when I first woke for work at 5:35am I was still feverish and achy, although I could tell I was better than I had been at my worst Sunday evening.  After going back to sleep, I woke up at 10am feeling significantly better.  Aside from being rather flushed and sweaty, I felt fine the rest of the day.  My injection site was mottled red, swollen, and painful for about three more days, with improvement every day.    I am not concerned about my reaction.  I am only reporting it to provide data.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1146, RRT was called at the post-vaccination monitoring area for an 85 y/o female that was experiencing tingling throughout left arm after administration of the Pfizer vaccine at 1132. No other symptoms reported. Client?s car was off and she was accompanied by her neighbor, who was seated on the passenger seat. Client was the driver at the time. 2 RRT nurses responded to the scene with the E-kit and stethoscope. Head-to-toe assessment done, all WNL. Client speaking clearly, able to extend both arms, face symmetrical. Bilateral arms and legs have equal strength. Initial HR: 65, BP: 117/70, RR: 20, denies pain. Client?s arm tingling did not get worse or better. 911 assistance not needed at this time. Client recommended to be monitored for an additional 10 minutes by Recovery Nurse. Client was encouraged to have neighbor drive her home, which she consented. After additional 10-minute monitoring period, left arm remained the same and client did not experience any other symptoms. Neighbor moved to the driver?s seat and client is now in the passenger seat. Client advised to speak to her PCP about incident and if SOB and/or life-threatening problems occur, to call 911 or get to the nearest hospital/ER. Client and neighbor verbalized understanding.  All questions answered, all concerns met. Client left premises, her neighbor driving, via car @ 1210. Client exited with head-to-toe assessment WNL.
OTHER_MEDS: None at the time of vaccination but on the morning of vaccination day today, she took a prescribed Antihistamine, Gabapentin, Tylenol, and Hydrochlorothiazide. She also took another HTN medication which she does not remember.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient had a very severe side effect profile from the second dose of vaccine:  "worst I've ever felt" with myalgia, headache, fever and fatigue.  This subsided and then on day 3 he developed severe substernal chest pain and came to ER where his hs-cTnI was > 2000 ng/L and peaked at 6700 ng/L.  His ECG, echo and cardiac cath were normal but MRI showed evidence of myocarditis with mild left ventricular dysfunction. He is doing well clinically and we are managing expectantly.   This appears to be immune mediated myocarditis from the Moderna vaccine
LAB_DATA: hs-cTnI peaked at 6700 CRP 19, ESR 25,  normal cath, ECG Markedly abnormal cardiac MRI with clear evidence myocarditis Negative COVID PCR x 2

SYMPTOM_TEXT: - Needed inhaler each night since     - Jan. 25th night was worst yet, took over an hour for inhaler to kick in. Tried steam and heating pad, little improvement  - Jan. 26th Took ProAir inhaler at 2pm before shift     - Little improvement     - Pain still in chest - Called my primary Dr. at 4:30     - Prescribed prednisone and Advair     - Thinks vaccine caused inflammatory response  - Took prednisone at 8pm - Took Advair around 11 - Took ProAir inhaler around midnight  - Heart racing (HR130) - SOB, pain when breathing  - Localized to sternum, on either side as if something was grabbing my lungs and squeezing  - Feel like lightning coursing thru my veins - Shaky  I ended the up in the ER Jan. 26th.  * I took prednisone at 8pm * I took Advair at 11pm * I was still having trouble breathing and my last hit of my ProAir had completely worn off * I took my ProAir around midnight  * Over the course of the next two hours I was SOB, tachy (HR 130s), hot and cold flashes, pain while breathing, couldn?t catch my breath * My friends took me to the ER around 2am * At the hospital they did a 12 Lead EKG, blood work, labs, 2 chest X-rays, and a COVID-test * They gave me 0.5 mg lorazepam IV  * All of my blood work and labs came back normal.  * X-rays came back clear * EKG came back fine * Negative COVID test * I took a nap after the lorazepam hit and woke up feeling much better * ER doc thinks my ProAir exacerbated some anxiety because my lungs were clear and no wheezing  * Discharged me with a script for lorazepam PRN x10 and instructions to follow up with my primary is back at home.  * Doc said I could continue the prednisone and Advair  * Woke up today and yesterday feeling better, still some pain when breathing and exhausted. Pain is mostly at top of my lungs, going across my chest. Deep breathing sometimes helps but there?s also pain upon inhalation.  * Took the next doses of Advair and my Dexedrine (ADHD meds). Nothing weird yet just drained.   They switched my Ventolin inhaler to ProAir, I have been taking it about five times a week so I can workout. When I was on Ventolin I didn?t have any of the side effects I have with ProAir.

Covid19 Employee Health replied in email with instructions to keep the appointment for Jan 15 and take covid test.. then my Manager sent me home.   Jan 12, as per advice, took my Covid19 swab test, turned out Negative ;   Jan 15, more pain and couldnt hold anything or even raise my left arm; in and around my left shoulder, chest, underarm and back are still swollen and tender. They are also expecting to send them paperworks related to this work injury/illness;  Jan 18, continuous monitoring, sore and swelling still exist; emailed me saying that they been notified for my injury/illness report; In the link of the email, it said that they will send me the documents packet to be filled out and my PCP is also expecting for the papers but havent recieved yet;   Jan 21, Yesterday was my 5th day of taking prednisone.. As of today, my left shoulder and around chest, underarm and back are still sore and swollen. The prednisone helped during the day but pain still present at night and when in bed. Some nights I hardly sleep even putting some pillows around.. During the day, I am trying to slowly raise my left arm holding it with my right hand and do some stretchings too. Despite all of these efforts, the progress is slow and pain is still exist. I sent an update to my PCP and to my Manager; My PCP sent me a reply saying that she would order for an Imaging but still waiting for the documents packet  to be filled out and signed but havent received it yet.   Jan 22, took pain med this morning, pain is just #5, but still hardly raise much of my left arm, still sore and swollen around my shoulder; chills and headace no longer present; i just experienced them on and off in my first 4 days after the 2nd dose; slowly raising my left arm with the help of my right hand; doing stretching too  Jan 25, 2021.  Today, I'm still out from work. my swollen left shoulder is subsiding but 'Im worried about the sore and swelling around it like in my chest, underarm and back. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe flu-like symptoms. Muscle pain, fatigue, lethargy, severe headache.

After the injection I started having slight nausea.  At the first night around 8:30pm I started having pain at the injection site.  I took Aleve for pain Friday morning. I started having severe pain to both armpits around 10am. Then around 11am I had severe chills and body aches. My temp was 101. I took some ibuprofen at that time. Then at noon my head started hurting and I had pain even in my fingers. I took more Aleve at 1pm. Around 3 I started to feel some relief.  That evening at 6:30 my symptoms worsened and I had chills so severe my whole body was shaking. I took some extra strength Tylenol and fell asleep. My husband work me around 9pm and I had a fever of 103. I took a shower and cooled down to 101.9. He kept watch over me all night and I slept very hard.  I woke up Saturday 8am with extreme fatigue and my lips began peeling when I brushed my teeth. I noticed I had swelling to all of my limbs and my face. My injection site was also swollen and painful including both armpits.  I stayed in bed all Saturday except for using the restroom.  I had no fever Saturday. Just aches and some dizziness and my brain was a little slower than usual. I also had almost no appetite.  I woke up around 8 Sunday morning with lessened body aches. Injection site swollen still but smaller about size of quarter instead of 50 cent piece. Still very tired. I wore my Apple Watch and it clocked my heart rate at low 50s while I as sleeping. I?m usually low 80s when I?m sleeping. Also Friday my watch clocked my heart rate at 110s while I was sitting still.  Appetite still less than normal. Brain still a little slow but I was able to leave the house for a bit.  It?s 8pm and I?m more alert but still not 100%.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Day 1 (day of vaccination): Within 15 minutes of receiving the jab i experienced heart palpitations, fever, dizziness, a dry mouth/throat and heat in my head/upper body. After being discharged from recovery an hour later i returned home but felt very anxious all night. Heart palpitations continued on and off. Day 2: Severe cramp/pain started in my arm, neck and shoulders. Headache. Sweating. Days 3 & 4: Flu symptoms; headache, shivers/fever, runny nose, sore throat, cough, severe muscle and joint pain. Skin was so sensitive to touch i could not wash. Muscles hurt so much i could not move around. Extreme fatigue. Days 5 & 6: Cold symptoms started to resolve. Muscle and joint pain still very severe - difficulty walking/moving around, stiffness and aches  in every part of my body. Extreme fatigue. Days 7, 8 & 9: Cold symptoms gone. Muscle and joint pain still severe. Extreme fatigue. Day 10: Pain in muscles started to resolve but not in joints. Fatigue still present. Day 11: Fatigue starting to resolve, joints still very sore.
LAB_DATA: None - GP made aware and advised to stay home and rest.

child's mother was vaccinated with VARIVAX after the delivery; chickenpox/ rash concerning for chickenpox/ Varicella Zoster Virus; meningitis/ varicella zoster virus/ VZV meningitis with cutaneous lesions; child's mother was vaccinated with VARIVAX after the delivery; the infant was breastfeeding at the time; This spontaneous report was received from a physician and refers to an 1-month-old (reported also as 3-week-old), female patient. The patient did not receive any concomitant medications, no known drug allergies (NKDA). She never had chickenpox, shingles or prior history of herpes zoster nor herpes zoster ophthalmicus reported.  On 20-DEC-2020, the patient's mother was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) 0.5 ml, in right arm, lot # T020652, upon internal validation was determined to be a valid lot #, expiration date was not reported but established as 16-JUN-2022 (strength and route of administration were not reported) since it was determined during a prenatal screen, that she was not immune to varicella (for prophylaxis). The physician was not sure, if the patient (baby) was in close contact or in the room at the time the mother was vaccinated. On approximately 09-JAN-2021 (reported as on 09-JAN-2021 to 11-JAN-2021), the patient's mother developed a rash. The patient (baby) was breastfeeding at the time the mother had developed a rash, and was switched to formula on an unknown date in January 2021 (reported also as shortly thereafter) (exposure via breast milk, exposure to vaccinated person).  On approximately 12-JAN-2021, reported as between 12-JAN-2021 and 13-JAN-2021, the patient developed rash. On an unspecified date in January 2021, a newborn presented to the hospital with a rash concerning for chickenpox (chickenpox) (sought medical attention). The patient presented a fever on admission and underwent clinical testing. Meningitis panel using cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) was analyzed and was positive for varicella zoster virus (VZV) (meningitis viral), also reported as VZV meningitis with cutaneous lesions. The physician wanted to send viral isolates. The time interval since exposure to vaccine was reported as immediate. The physician reported possible secondary transmission, rash vesicles of over 100 lesions; generalized rash- chickenpox, and meningitis with positive VZV polymerase chain reaction (PCR) test in CSF (secondary transmission). Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) showed leptomeningeal enhancement and confirmed varicella meningitis. On approximately 14-JAN-2021, the patient started antiviral treatment with intravenous (IV) acyclovir (reported also as an oral antivirals). On the same date, before the treatment, the specimen sample was collected from the patient's CSF. On an unspecified date in January 2021, CSF red blood cells (RBC)  result was of 4200 (unit not provided), CSF glucose of 58 (unit not provided) and CSF white blood cells (WBC) of 17 (unit not provided). It was reported, that the treatment included also unspecified "antibacterials".  On 18-JAN-2021, at the day # 4 of the acyclovir treatment, the specimen was collected from the patient's forehead and bilateral lower extremities vesicle/lesion.  On 19-JAN-2021, the call was made to physician to confirm receiving requested program information. On that date, the patient was currently on day # 5 of acyclovir treatment and was clinically feeling okay, did not have fever. The physician was not sure, if they would send samples to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) or another lab or if would participate in the Program, since the physician would need to discuss further with the manager. The physician provided additional case information regarding the newborn. The program information was e-mailed to the physician as requested. The physician had additional questions upon receipt of the program information and an additional phone call was made. Upon speaking with the physician during the second call, the reporter stated, that they would like to send samples through the Program. Detailed shipping instructions were provided and reviewed including instructions about how to store a CSF sample frozen and additional case information was received. Additionally, the physician reported, that one lesion sample from the patient was obtained from 3 skin lesions and placed on transport media on day 4 of acyclovir treatment. After reading the program information, the physician wanted to know if this sample would be adequate to test since it was placed on transport media. The physician would try to obtain a fresh rash sample without transport media on the morning of 20-JAN-2021 to submit for testing.   The physician also stated, that the patient had some blisters remaining, but most had dried up "at this point". The physician would like to submit a 1 ml frozen sample for strain identification (CSF was obtained prior to the start of acyclovir and unspecified "antibacterials").  On 20-JAN-2021, at the day # 6 of acyclovir treatment, a call was made to the physician to help arrange for the shipping of samples. On that day, the specimen sample was collected from the patient's right foot vesicle/lesion. The physician confirmed, that there would be four total samples sent: 1 ml of CSF from infant stored frozen (collected prior to the start of "antivirals"), 1 lesion swab from the patient collected on day 4 of acyclovir treatment and placed on transport media, 1 lesion swab from the patient collected on day 5 of acyclovir treatment stored in a dry container, and 1 lesion scab from the mother's abdomen. The patient reportedly did not have any known health issues, was doing awesome and very well at the time of a call, but had performed an immunological work-up for further evaluation. The call concluded with discussion that all four samples would be picked up by the courier by the end of business.  On 25-JAN-2021 it was confirmed by the physician, that the 3 patient's specimens were sent to the laboratory on 20-JAN-2021. The samples were delivered. The results were still not obtained. The outcome of the events was recovering/resolving. Additional information has been requested. The causality between the suspect vaccine and the events was not provided.  The patient was enrolled in the Program to identify if VZV is present and if it is present, to identify if it is associated with the wild-type (WT) VZV strain or with the Oka/Merck vaccine strain.  Upon internal review, the event meningitis viral was determined to be medically significant.  This is one of the two linked reports of mother and child (the mother's case # 2101USA011308).; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2101USA011308:

Follow-up information was received from a lawyer on 04-FEB-2020, regarding a case in litigation and refers to a 69-year-old male patient. In 2013 (conflicting with information received previously from program), the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine adult health maintenance for the prevention of shingles. The vaccine did not prevent shingles as intended, and the patient subsequently contracted a persistent strain condition of herpes zoster. On or about 23-APR-2014, patient was treated by a healthcare provider for a blistering vesicular outbreak, which was diagnosed as shingles. Patient was prescribed gabapentin and acyclovir for management of his painful symptoms and chronic pain. On or about 21-FEB-2017, patient sought subsequent treatment from a healthcare provider for a blistering vesicular outbreak, which was diagnosed as herpes zoster. Patient was again prescribed gabapentin and acyclovir for management of his painful symptoms and chronic pain. As a direct and proximate result of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), and/or despite receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for long-term prevention of shingles, patient suffered painful injuries and damages, and required extensive medical care and treatment. As a further proximate result, patient has suffered and will continue to suffer significant medical expenses, and pain and suffering, and other damages. The outcome of the events was unknown. Follow-up information was received on 22-JAN-2021 from a lawyer via a Plaintiff Fact Sheet, concerning the 69-year-old male patient (pt). Pt's medical history included chicken pox. He had never received varicella vaccine. He was a non-smoker. On 01-DEC-2013 (conflicting with information received previously from program), the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) in the left arm. The pt claimed that as a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), he experienced shingles (herpes zoster), postherpetic neuralgia (PHN) and neurological injury (occipital neuralgia). Pt experienced severe pain on his left arm with temporary loss of movement of this arm for approximately 4 months. He first became aware of the injury on approximately 20-APR-2014. Pt saw the blisters, went to the doctor and asked him about it because he thought it was sun poisoning. Doctor did a biopsy and called 2 days later to let pt know it was shingles. Diagnosis of shingles was made by a physician on 20-APR-2020 and 24-APR-2020 and "shingles" gel (not specified), acyclovir and gabapentin were prescribed; diagnosis of PHN was made on 23-MAY-2014; and with occipital neuralgia on 21-FEB-2017. No test was performed by a Health Care Provider to determine if the rash was wild type or vaccine strain varicella zoster virus. No Health Care Provider ever told the pt that he had vaccine strain varicella zoster virus. Pt claimed that his receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) did not cause or aggravate any psychiatric and/or psychological condition(s) (other than pain and suffering and emotional distress). In the 7 years preceding zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination to the present, the pt received inpatient or outpatient care from health care providers for the following conditions: prostate problems (dates of care/treatment: 2007-2015), urology/prostate problems (dates of care/treatment: 2015-present), pneumonia (dates of care/treatment: 25-AUG-2019-December 2019), blood clot in lung (dates of care/treatment: 25-AUG-2019-December 2019). The pt was diagnosed with the following medical conditions for which she required hospitalization or recurrent medical care and treatment or medication in the 7 years preceding zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination to the present: high blood pressure (dates of care/treatment: 2000-present), prostate (dates of care/treatment: 2014-present), pneumonia (dates of care/treatment: 25-AUG-2019 to 05-SEP-2019), blood clot in lung (dates of care/treatment: August 2019 to April 2020). In the 7 years preceding zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination to the present, the pt had taken on a regular basis the following prescription medications: valsartan (DIOVAN) (2000-present) for high blood pressure, tadalafil (2006-present) for kidney flow/prostate, prednisone (30-JUL-2012 to 09-AUG-2012) (pt did not recall the indication), azithromycin (15-NOV-2012 to 21-NOV-2012) (pt did not recall the indication), amoxicillin (19-NOV-2012 to 29-DEC-2012) (pt did not recall the indication), hydrocodone (+) acetaminophen (22-APR-2014 to 22-JUN-2014) for kidney stone, apixaban (ELIQUIS) (25-AUG-2019 to 01-APR-2020) for blood clot in lung, amoxicillin (+) clavulanate potassium (AUGMENTIN) (25-AUG-2019 to 05-SEP-2019) for pneumonia. The pt also received the following vaccinations: pneumococcal vaccine (manufacturer unknown) on 01-DEC-2013; diphtheria toxoid (+) pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified) (+) tetanus toxoid in 2014; and influenza vaccine on 01-OCT-2019.   Follow-up information was received on 22-JAN-2021 via medical records. Pt was a former smoker (also reported as never smoker, conflicting information). Use of alcohol: 0-2 drinks per day. His concurrent conditions included high blood pressure. Surgical history included: adenoidectomy, tonsillectomy, urinary tract surgery (microwave of prostate, spermatocele) and vasectomy. Family history included cancer and diabetes mellitus. Pt's concomitant medications included tadalafil (CIALIS), valsartan (DIOVAN) and ascorbic acid. Office visit (OV) on 23-APR-2014: pt came with with a complaint of rash on left shoulder for about 1 week. It looked like shingles. "Shingles" gel (not specified), acyclovir and gabapentin were prescribed. OV on 30-APR-2014: pt still having pain up back of neck and into head, shingles in the C3-C5 dermatomes; present on the left side. He continued to have headaches present on the base of skull on the left. He used one dose of hydrocodone. There was a resolving zoster rash noted on the left C3-C5 dermatome, there were a few scattered erythematous lesions noted on the left flank area near the fourth and fifth thoracic dermatome. Assessment: herpes zoster. Gabapentin dose was increased.   Follow-up information was received on 25-JAN-2021 from the lawyer. In 2013, the pt was administered zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for the long-term prevention of shingles and zoster-related conditions. Subsequently, pt was treated by a healthcare provider for the following injuries resulting from zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use: shingles and other zoster related injuries.  Information received via medical records on 22-JAN-2021 contained additional adverse experiences: codeine allergy (22-APR-2013, outcome and causality unknown (UNK), nausea (23-APR-2014, outcome and causality UNK), passing out (23-APR-2014, outcome and causality UNK), Postoccipital headache (probably secondary to herpes zoster) (??-APR-2014, outcome and causality UNK).  Upon internal review, the events of blood clot in lung, pneumonia, kidney stone and passing out were considered to be medically significant.  All available medical records will be provided upon request.  The serious criterion of disability was deleted for shingles, since medical records did not confirm this information.  It has been determined that case # US-009507513-2003USA007278 is a duplicate of case # US-MERCK-1404USA013963. Therefore, case # US-009507513-2003USA007278 is being deleted from our files and the cases are consolidated into case # US-MERCK-1404USA013963.

The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.  On 18-Nov-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59; dose reported as one; route of administration: intramuscular; anatomical location: left arm; indication: not reported). The batch number reported was 290706.  On the same day, after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient had very severe reaction to the flu shot: fever, flu like symptoms, nausea, felt like vomiting, muscle aches and joint issues.  The outcome of the events was unknown.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment, but the patient's daughter assessed the events as related to Fluad Quadrivalent.  The case was assessed as non-serious.  Additional information received on 19-Jan-2021 via Product Technical Complaint (PTC) group: After batch number mapping, suspect product was re-coded from Fluad (TIV) to Fluad Quadrivalent. The narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: A 85-year-old female patient experienced arthropathy, influenza like illness, pyrexia, nausea and myalgia on the same day after administration of Fluad Quadrivalent. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. Hot, itchy orange-sized lump at injection site; Hot, itchy orange-sized lump at injection site; Local allergic reaction; Hot, itchy orange-sized lump at injection site; This is a spontaneous case was received on 05-Jan-2021, reported by pharmacist to regulatory authority (reference number: SEQW21-00039) and concerned a 67-year-old, female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions were not reported. The patient's past medical history included breast cancer. The patient stated that she was not allergic to eggs. The patient's concomitant medication included Aromasin (exemestane) for an unreported indication.  On 04-Nov-2019, the patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular and anatomical: not reported) for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number reported was 259815, expiry date: 30-Jun-2020.  On the same day, within 15 minutes after receiving Flucelvax Quadrivalent, the patient experienced hot, itchy orange-sized lump at injection. She had a very significant local allergic reaction and in half an hour post vaccination the patient was seen by attending physician. Prednisolone at dose of 20 mg and Benadryl (diphenhydramine hydrochloride) at dose of 15 mg were given as corrective treatment.   On the same day, within four to six hours, the patient recovered from the events.  The reporter assessed all events as related to Flucelvax Quadrivalent, as the patient had shown allergy to flu vaccine and stated that there must be some lingering, 'hidden', maybe trace ingredient which was responsible for the patient's allergy.   The case was assessed as non-serious.  Company comment: A 67-year-old patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax Quadrivalent. On the same day, within 15 minutes after receiving Flucelvax Quadrivalent, the patient experienced vaccination site mass, vaccination site warmth, vaccination site pruritus and local allergic reaction. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt received Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine Dose 1 at 0837. At 0843 pt started to complain of numbness and tingling in bilateral hands, right worse than left. Shaky feeling. Lightheadedness. Slight nausea. No dyspnea or numbness/tingling in face, neck, or throat. HR: 84 BP: 147/78 SP02: 95%-96%. At 0845, pt given apple juice and saltine crackers. Cool rags applied to neck. Stayed in room with pt to monitor. At 0900 pt laying back in chair, states she is feeling a bit better. HR: 74 BP: 128/73 SP02: 99%. At 0910, pt states that she is starting to feel like her throat is swelling and Convenient Care staff present by 0911. At 0913, pt was taken over to Convenient Care via wheelchair.  At convenient care, pt presented with possible allergic reaction where she reported an allergy to peanuts and that she "has had reactions to other things". She had an injection site reaction to her first influenza vaccine (unknown year), but now receives them annually without issue. Pt reports she feels her hands are swelling, as her rings feel tight and that is not usually the case. Pt given diphenhydramine 50 mg IM x 1 and BP improved from 175/84 to 154/90. At 0940, pt reported she felt the lump in her throat was better and the rings on her fingers are looser. Pt spent about 1 hour at convenient care before pt was discharged to home. Pt diagnosed with allergic reaction to COVID-19 vaccine.

The evening of Friday January 29th my face began to experience itching and burning as well as hive like bumps. I did not take anything for that at the time. I woke up the next morning with my face extremely sensitive with red splotches and it was still very itchy. I then noticed the arm that had the injection was hard and was also experiencing the same symptoms as my face and increased soreness. I took Benadryl that evening and woke up Sunday with improved symptoms but still noticeable soreness in the area of the injection and it was still a little red and hot to the touch. It is now Monday morning and the reaction has continued to improve with still some soreness and a little hot to the touch.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2.5 hours after the injection I developed left arm swelling, itching with erythemia as well as, severe headache, nausea, GI turbulence, fatigue, and chills. I had to stop working that day and the next day. The headache was unrelenting. I went to bed with a heating pad on my head. Typically my body temp is 97.3 it went up to 98.1 I took Ibuprofen and Benadryl around the clock for the next 10 days. Day 8 & 9 were the worst. My arm looked like an orange at the site of the injection; it was red/inflamed, induration & itched. The welt size 2" x 1". My headache was intractable, severe chills with teeth chattering, nausea, GI turbulence. It was a horrible 48 hours at which time I was again not able to work. I finally felt better on day 10. On day 14 my arm finally looked like it had not had an injection in it.
LAB_DATA: None. Contacted my doctor by phone.  He said I was making antibodies.
ALLERGIES: Latex, latex based food- banana, avocado, tomato, lettuce, cucumber, watermelon, kiwi etc. Environmental- dust, dust mites, mold Feathers Birch bark Multiple chemical sensitivities

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient reported that her doctor told her that she has a condition called bronchiectasis; COPD; Emphysema; Bronchitis; but still got Pneumonia in December 2015; pneumonia; This spontaneous report was received from a female patient of unknown age via Pfizer (manufacturer control number 2016076426), referring to herself. The patient never smoked. The patient's concurrent conditions, pertinent medical history and concomitant therapies were not reported.     In February 2015, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (Lot#, expiration date, strength, dose and route of administration were not reported) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient experienced chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), emphysema and bronchitis.   On 22-DEC-2015, the patient experienced pneumonia.   At the reporting time, the outcome of COPD, emphysema, bronchitis and pneumonia was not reported.   The causal assessment between the events and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was unknown.  Follow up information was received from the patient on 28-MAR-2016. The patient reported that her doctor told her that she had a condition called bronchiectasis, on an unspecified date. She also reported that she would be getting a computarised tomography scan of her lungs on a future (unspecified date).   Follow up information was received from the patient on 25-JAN-2021. The patient reported receiving pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) in February 2015 but still got pneumonia in December 2015 (vaccination failure). The patient provided permission to contact her current nurse practitioner but stated this was not the person who administered the vaccine in 2015.

anxiety.; eyes rolled back and she appeared to be having a mild seizure; lethargic; nauseated; syncopal episode/passed out/loss of consciousness; Information has been received from the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) (Vaccine Adverse Experience Report on 04-SEP-2020.  This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse and refers to a 15-years-old, non-pregnant female patient. It was unknown if she took any prescriptions, over-the-counter medications, dietary supplements, or herbal remedies at the time of vaccination. She had no allergies to medications, food or other products. It was not reported if she had other illnesses at the time of vaccination and up to one month prior, and no chronic or long-standing health conditions. The patient's mother verbalized no known previous reactions to any vaccines.  On 19-SEP-2019 at 11:20, the patient was vaccinated with her first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) administrated intramuscularly into the left arm (dose was not provided; lot # N020353 was confirmed to be valid; expiration date was not reported but upon internal validation process, it was established as 28-APR-2020) for prophylaxis. On the same date, she also received the first dose of hepatitis a virus vaccine inactivated (HAVRIX) into right arm (lot number PA99T; dose, strength and expiration date was not provided); diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular 5-component vaccine, tetanus toxoid (ADACEL) into left arm (lot number U6378AA; dose, strength and expiration date was not provided), and meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA) also into right arm (lot number U6543AA; dose, strength and expiration date was not provided). All vaccines were administrated intramuscularly for prophylaxis. During administration of meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA) and hepatitis a virus vaccine inactivated (HAVRIX) vaccines the patient was conversing with the reporter and her mother throughout but was showing some anxiety. After that, the left arm vaccines were given of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) and diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular 5-component vaccine, tetanus toxoid (ADACEL). Shortly after completed with left arm vaccinations, the patient's eyes rolled back and she appeared to be having a mild seizure. She laid back on a table. She passed for around 15 seconds, she sat up with help but was very lethargic. She said she was nauseated. the patient's mother went to waiting room to get family member while the nurse stayed with the patient. On return they discussed visiting her doctor or the emergency room. The patient family member attempted to carry her out and she passed out again in hallway. She was held and eased down to floor by family. the patient was not harmed during transfer. The nurse called 911 to have patient evaluated for safety purposes. No allergic reaction evident, no redness, hives or breathing issues, just what appeared as a mild initial seizure and fainting episodes. the patient was evaluated by emergency medical services (EMS). Blood sugar and vitals were within normal limits. She was transported to local emergency room (ER) for evaluation. The reporter has provided vaccination Information and her contact information to the patient's mother. It was unknown if the patient recovered from the adverse events.  The relatedness between the aforementioned events and the suspect vaccines was not provided. The case was assessed by the FDA as non-serious.  Follow up information has been received from the registered nurse on 25-JAN-2021 via questionnaire. The patient had no previous reactions to vaccines. On 19-SEP-2019, the patient was vaccinated with 4 vaccines hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) lot # U6378AA (conflicting information, previously reported as N020353 which was valid lot # for hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9), lot # U6378AA is an invalid lot number for hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9). Lot number U6378AA does not match any Company product as confirmed by Lot Verification team), therapies included diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular 5-component vaccine, tetanus toxoid (ADACEL) lot # PA99T (conflicting information, previously reported as U6378AA), hepatitis a virus vaccine inactivated (HAVRIX) lot # N020353 (conflicting information, previously reported as PA99T) and meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA). Previously reported events were further described. On the same date, once completed vaccinations, while the patient was sitting on an exam table, the patient became lethargic, eye-rolling, than syncopal episode (also reported as loss of consciousness). The nurse called for ambulance, and the patient was taken to ER to be evaluated and to rule out seizure or reaction to vaccines. The nurse reported possible seizures, but it was reported that the ER physician assessed the event not a seizure, only severe anxiety and not a vaccine reaction, therefore event seizure was deleted. The nurse talked with the patient's mother 2 hours after the event, and she stated that the patient was doing well, and the outcome of became lethargic, eye-rolling and syncopal episode was reported as recovered. The patient was sent home from the ER. The causality assessment between the events and the suspect vaccines was not provided. Upon internal review the events of syncope was determined to be medically significant.

Immediately after receiving the 2nd dose of the Pfizer vaccine, I had muscle pain at the injection site and difficulty lifting that arm the next day (similar reaction as after the 1st dose). I received the vaccine Wednesday evening (6 p.m.) on 1/13/21. Around 2 p.m. the next day, I started having a fever (over 101 degrees); chills; body aches; and fatigue. These symptoms lasted for three days but the fever was slowly going down with Advil. By Saturday evening, my symptoms changed to headaches and diarrhea, which lasted for an additional three days after that. My nose suddenly started running the following afternoon (Wednesday, 1/20/21) for about an hour and then that stopped and did not recur. All symptoms were gone by Thursday, 1/21/21 and I had none of these symptoms prior to taking the second dose of the vaccine (other than the arm pain for 1-2 days following the 1st dose of the vaccine).

I woke up in the middle of the night with a 102.7 fever, severe migraine, severe body aches, leg cramps, sore throat/swelling, and chills. I alternated taking ibuprofen and tylenol to try to control the pain, to no avail. I used bengay and cool washcloths for pain and to cool off. These did not help either. I made sure to keep drinking water and pedialyte. I took benadryl to try to sleep and help with my throat swelling up, it did not help.  All of this was non-stop until the morning of the 30th. That morning when I woke up my fever was going down and I no longer had the chills. I still had the severe headache, body pains, cramping, swollen/sore throat, and now diarrhea. HCP approached vehicle where a 68yo white male was sitting in his vehicle on the driver side. Quick assessment revealed erythema of the face and angioedema. Pt was able to speak clearly, was CTA and had RRR. 911 was called. BP 160/90.  EpiPen dose 1 was injected into right vastus lateralis and pt reported improvement at 1057.  HCP asked for injectable diphenhydramine. HCP continued to monitor pt with RRR and CTA but erythema and angioedema began again along with swollen tongue so EpiPen dose 2 was injected into right vastus lateralis. 50mg IM diphenhydramine was injected into the right deltoid while fire rescue began to arrive on scene. Pt did not report difficulty breathing. Pt did report previous anaphylaxis to fire ant bites/stings and did report being allergic to bee stings. Fire rescue transported patient without difficulty. HCP called pt later that night at 2030 who reported doing better but still having tongue swelling.
